Japan: BayCurrent Consulting’s IPO to provide exit for CLSA’s Sunrise fund























 Temple in Kiyomizu,Japan. Credit:Flickr/Caribb


 





Anirvan Ghosh 




                    September 2, 2016                

CLSA Capital Partners, the alternative asset management arm of CLSA, today announced an initial public offering of BayCurrent Consulting, Inc. on Mothers market of Tokyo Stock Exchange.
The IPO provides an exit for Sunrise Capital II, the CLSA Capital Partners’ buyout fund that invests in established, mid-cap companies with strong growth potential in Japan.
“Securing independent management and operations through an IPO is key to ensuring that BayCurrent continues to provide clients superior, customised and unbiased solutions,” said Megumi Kiyozuka, Head of Sunrise Japan.
Baycurrent, based in Tokyo, is a consulting firm that focusses on IT and digital domains. CLSA had invested in the company through Sunrise II fund in June 2014. The fund has also worked with BayCurrent’s management to improve its quality of services and organization.
CLSA said the stock will begin trading from September 2 under the symbol ‘6532’. The company will offer a total of 50,000 shares.
The nominal offering price is 2,360 yen per share, for 118 million yen ($1.2 million) in total, as of the filing date of registration statement. The fixed offering price will be announced at a later date, CLSA said in the statement.
Nomura Securities Co., Ltd will be the underwriter for this offer.
CLSA’s Sunrise Capital fund series supports invested companies with overseas expansion through CLSA’s global network. It has invested in nine companies since the fund series was established in 2006.
Current portfolio includes tutoring business KK BC Holdings, auto maintenance tools retailer Worldtool, F&B firm Asamiya and consulting service provider BayCurrent Consulting.
CLSA Capital Partners is the wholly-owned alternative asset-management arm of CLSA, Asia’s leading brokerage and investment group. It manages $3 billion assets and operates seven offices located in Hong Kong, Singapore and Tokyo.
